summary: Pokemon concept
title: Pokemon concept
body: A tail that functions as a scarf or mane. I got this idea from a strange thought I had just now with a subversion of Litten and the fact that some of my favourite Pokemon have tails that work as something else. Skuntank with the tail covering most of the top of its body and looks like a tuft of hair on its head, Purugly with its tail being a cushion that pushes the Pokemon’s stomach fat to make it look more intimidating and now for something totally different!

blog.title: Professor Pines's Pokémon Posts
blog.description: I'm Professor Lilia Pines, ask me about pokémon! ((Headcanon/roleplay blog))

summary: Hi professor! I'm a Pokémon Coordinator with a Vanilluxe, a Leafeon and my main partner; Luxray! Recently I received an egg from...
question: Hi professor! I'm a Pokémon Coordinator with a Vanilluxe, a Leafeon and my main partner; Luxray! Recently I received an egg from a friend, and after some research I believe it's a Kantonian Vulpix egg! My team and I have been with the four of us for seven years now and I've never had an egg before, so this is quite exciting! Is there anything I should keep in mind for when Vulpix hatches?
answer:
First of all, I would like to say that I do like how every pokémon here except your leafeon has an X somewhere in its name. You can be the X-trainer! …or perhaps not.

Vulpixes primarily eat meat, or commercial vulpix food if you would prefer yours not hunt. They need open spaces to run around, both indoors and outdoors, and chew toys, balls, soft toys, etc. Actually, care for a vulpix is very similar to care for an eevee, so if you still have some of your leafeon’s old toys, you can either give those to your vulpix or buy new ones of the same sort. Additionally, you can refer to this post if you need details about how to raise the vulpix. If your leafeon, in particular, is willing to play surrogate parent, you will mostly have to worry about feeding, and can skim over the parts about cleaning the kit. 

However, you should keep in mind that vulpixes are fire-types, and while their fire powers are not particularly strong when they’re young, they do need more warmth than an eevee would; it’s recommended that their living spaces are kept around 22°C (71.6°F), though newborns without mothers to warm them will need somewhat higher temperatures for the first few weeks. Vulpixes are also capable of warming themselves by breathing small fireballs, which is an option if you’d rather not keep the house at summer temperatures, but this can be dangerous if flammable objects (or your leafeon) are around. If your leafeon does decide to act as a surrogate parent to the vulpix, the high temperature of either the room or the vulpix may be uncomfortable for it, so you might be better suited hand-raising the vulpix until it’s old enough to handle relatively cooler temperatures.

Finally, vulpixes rarely shed, but they are very proud of their coats, so you will need to brush your vulpix daily to keep it smooth and shiny; otherwise, it’s prone to dulling and matting, which will make your vulpix very unhappy.

Congratulations on your new teammate! I hope this helps!
